body:
Can you please share the model? If the MatMul node doesn't have much work to do due to the input size the benefit of quantization would be limited.

What processor does the machine have? If it's say 32-bit ARM we may not have an optimized kernel for that currently.

Hi, sorry I can not share the model without permission, below is the MatMul I showed, bs=1:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/65003808/147728789-46b089a5-f589-4ff1-a156-013b8327b70d.png)
My processer is Intel(R) Xeon(R) Platinum 8280L CPU @ 2.70GHz
Thanks

@mengniwang95, it should be able to get perf gain on Xeon 8280L. The subgraph you shared should be fused into one op, but from the profiling you shared, they are not fused. Did you set graph_optimization_level manually?

@yufenglee yes, I use DISABLE_ALL. 
I find if I use thread_num=1 int8 model can get obvious perf gain, is this because the quantized node has more work to do?
Could you please share the perf number with different threads? Even though we parallel quantization logic, it plateaus with less threads than matmul, thus leads to relatively higher overhead.

The perf looks expected. Quantized MatMul gets best perf speedup(3~4x) with single thread because overhead of quantization is relative small comparing the cost of MatMul computation. With more threads, quantization part gets less speedup than MatMul and the overhead become relatively higher and eventually plateau at 1.5~2x speedup.
